      "shortTitle": "The Treaty",
      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT 1: THE TRUCKHOUSE PROMISE",
      "interactionPrompt": "FIELD ANALYSIS: Does Article 4 of the 1752 Treaty support a right to sell modern goods? Cite evidence from the 'Truckhouse' context.",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## The 1752 Agreement\nIn 1752, the Mi'kmaq and the British Crown signed a Treaty of Peace and Friendship. This was not a document of surrender; it was a strategic alliance between two nations. At the time, the British were struggling to keep control of Nova Scotia and wanted to stop the Mi'kmaq from helping the French. The Mi'kmaq, in return, wanted to protect their way of life and ensure their people could survive in a world where European settlers were taking more and more land. A central part of this deal was the promise of 'Truckhouses'—special government-run trading posts where the Mi'kmaq could bring their furs, skins, and feathers to trade for blankets, tools, and food. The British promised that these truckhouses would offer fair prices, ensuring the Mi'kmaq wouldn't be cheated by dishonest private merchants.\n\nToday, Leo argues that the *spirit* of this promise—the 'Truckhouse'—was never meant to be frozen in time. He believes that if the British promised a place to trade in 1752, the modern government cannot now make that trade 'illegal' simply because the product has changed from beaver pelts to cannabis. His shop, 'The Trading Post,' is named specifically to remind the government of this 270-year-old promise. For Leo, this isn't just about selling a product; it's about the inherent right of the Mi'kmaq to participate in the economy. He argues that the treaty was a guarantee of economic survival, and that the government's current monopoly on cannabis is a violation of that ancient bond.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/truckhouse-map.jpg",
          "credit": "AI Historical Reconstruction"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## The 'Any Other Thing' Clause\nArticle 4 of the 1752 Treaty is the legal foundation of Leo's defense. It states: 'It is agreed that the said Indians shall have free liberty to bring for Sale to Halifax or any other Settlement... any other thing they shall have to Sell.' The defense argues that the phrase 'any other thing' is deliberately broad. It wasn't just about fish or furs; it was a general right to trade. If the Mi'kmaq had items of value in 1752, they had the 'liberty' to sell them. In the 1999 *Marshall* decision, the Supreme Court of Canada already ruled that these treaties give Mi'kmaw people a right to hunt and fish to earn a 'moderate livelihood.' The legal question now is: does 'any other thing' include modern, highly regulated substances like cannabis?\n\nThis brings us to the **Living Tree Doctrine**. In Canadian law, the Constitution and its treaties are viewed as a living thing that must grow and adapt to modern times. Judges are not supposed to interpret a treaty exactly as people did in 1752; they must look at the 'intent.' If the intent was to allow the Mi'kmaq to trade for their survival, then as the economy changes, the items they trade must be allowed to change too. However, the Crown disagrees. They argue that 'any other thing' only referred to items that were common and legal in the 18th century. They claim that cannabis, which requires laboratory testing and strict government control, is a completely different category of trade that the treaty signers never could have imagined.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/leo-chief-justice-letter-AI.jpg",
          "credit": "National Archives Mockup"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## The Wampum Record\nIntelligence reports from Mi'kmaw elders and historians emphasize that treaties are not just pieces of paper; they are sacred covenants often recorded in **Wampum Belts**. Unlike a British contract, which is static and fixed, Wampum represents a relationship between living peoples that must be renewed and respected over time. To the Mi'kmaq, the 1752 Treaty was a 'Peace and Friendship' pact that recognized their status as a sovereign nation with the right to be self-sufficient. Trade was seen as a way to maintain that sovereignty—if you can trade for what you need, you don't have to depend on government handouts.\n\nStrategic analysis of the current situation shows that Leo’s shop is more than a business; it’s a cultural reclamation project. By using the 'Trading Post' name, he is signaling that he does not recognize the Province’s authority to tell him what he can and cannot sell on traditional territory. Intel suggests that the community sees the shop as a success because it provides jobs and funding for local youth programs. If the court rules against Leo, intelligence forecasts suggest it will be viewed not just as a legal loss, but as a modern-day violation of the sacred Wampum covenant. This could lead to a 'reconciliation crisis,' where the Mi'kmaq lose faith in the Canadian court system altogether, potentially leading to more direct actions like blockades.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/wampum-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "Cultural Heritage Intel"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "slide_2",
      "shortTitle": "The Raid",
      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT 2: THE CONFLICT OF LAWS",
      "interactionPrompt": "FIELD ANALYSIS: Was the provincial raid a justified use of force, or did it violate the 'Honour of the Crown'?",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## Operation High Tide\nThe legal debate turned into a physical confrontation during 'Operation High Tide.' In a coordinated series of raids, provincial police officers wearing tactical gear arrived at 'The Trading Post' and several other Indigenous-run dispensaries. They used bolt cutters to break into storage rooms, seized thousands of dollars of product, and arrested staff members. To the Province of Nova Scotia, this was a standard law enforcement operation meant to shut down 'unregulated' businesses that were operating without a provincial license. They argued that these shops were cutting into the revenue of the government-run NSLC stores and creating an unfair market.\n\nHowever, for Leo and the Sipekne’katik community, the raid felt like an act of aggression. They pointed out that 'The Trading Post' was not 'illegal' in their eyes—it was authorized by a **Band Council Resolution (BCR)**. This is a law passed by the local Indigenous government. This creates a massive conflict: can a provincial police force enter a First Nation community and arrest people for following their own local laws? The images of armed officers on reserve land went viral instantly, sparking a national debate about whether the government is using 'public safety' as an excuse to shut down Indigenous economic competition. The raid didn't just stop sales; it created a sense of siege within the community.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/rcmp-protest-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## Jurisdictional Conflict\nThe core of the legal fight is about 'Jurisdiction'—the power to make and enforce laws. Under Section 91 of the Constitution, the Federal government has the power over 'Indians and Lands reserved for Indians.' Under Section 92, the Provinces have power over 'Property and Civil Rights.' When cannabis was legalized in 2018, the Federal government gave the Provinces the right to decide how to sell it. The Province of Nova Scotia argues that because cannabis is a 'property' item, their laws of 'general application' should apply to everyone, regardless of whether they are on a reserve or not. They claim that a Band Council cannot simply 'opt out' of provincial health and safety rules.\n\nLeo’s legal team argues that this is a 'jurisdictional vacuum.' They believe that because Indigenous rights are **Sui Generis** (unique), they fall outside the normal rules of the province. They argue that under Section 35, the right to trade is a 'constitutionally protected' right, which is higher than a 'provincial law.' In their view, a provincial law cannot be used to destroy a treaty right. This is one of the most difficult questions for the Supreme Court: when two different governments (the Province and the First Nation) make two different laws for the same piece of land, whose law wins? If the Province wins, it sets a precedent that provincial regulations can override almost any treaty right. If Leo wins, it could mean that First Nations have the power to create their own economic laws that the province cannot touch.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/police-line-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## Safety vs. Revenue\nIntelligence gathered from internal government emails suggests that the motivation for the raids was not purely about health. Reports show that the Nova Scotia Liquor Corporation (NSLC) had been complaining about a significant loss in sales. Because Indigenous shops like Leo’s do not have to pay provincial sales tax or follow provincial pricing, their product is much cheaper. This 'economic intel' indicates that the Province was worried about their monopoly. Publicly, the police and the Premier stated the raids were about 'public safety' and protecting people from 'untested products' that might contain mould or harmful chemicals. They claimed that without provincial testing, the community was at risk.\n\nHowever, 'field intel' from 'The Trading Post' tells a different story. Leo’s shop actually used private labs to test their products, and they argue their standards were often higher than the government’s. They claim that the 'public safety' argument is a 'red herring'—a distraction used to hide the real goal of protecting tax revenue. Strategic analysis shows that by framing the issue as 'safety,' the Province can justify using police force, which is easier than negotiating a new economic treaty. The intelligence community is watching to see if the Crown can prove a real 'safety risk' in court, or if the evidence shows that this was truly about protecting the government's wallet.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/leo-test-report.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "slide_3",
      "shortTitle": "The Defense",
      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT 3: THE RIGHT TO A LIVELIHOOD",
      "interactionPrompt": "FIELD ANALYSIS: Apply the Sparrow Test. Did the government have a 'compelling objective' to limit Leo's right? Cite the 4 steps.",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## The Marshall Legacy\nTo understand Leo's defense, we have to look back at the case of Donald Marshall Jr. In the 1990s, Marshall was arrested for catching and selling eels without a license. He argued that his ancestors had signed treaties with the British in 1760 that protected his right to fish. In 1999, the Supreme Court of Canada agreed with him. They ruled that the treaties give Mi'kmaw people a right to hunt, fish, and gather to earn a **Moderate Livelihood**. This was a landmark decision because it proved that treaty rights were not just about 'survival' in the past, but about 'economic participation' in the present. It meant that Mi'kmaw people had a constitutional right to run businesses based on natural resources.\n\nLeo’s lawyers are arguing that 'The Trading Post' is the 21st-century version of the Marshall case. If the court protected the right to sell eels, why wouldn't it protect the right to sell cannabis? They argue that the resource doesn't matter as much as the *purpose*—which is to earn a livelihood. They point out that cannabis is a plant, a natural resource, and that trading it is a modern way for a Mi'kmaw person to support their family. The defense is trying to convince the Justices that 'livelihood' should be interpreted broadly. If the government can decide what counts as a 'traditional' resource, they can effectively kill any new Indigenous business before it starts. The defense's goal is to show that Leo is simply exercising the 'Marshall Right' in a modern retail setting.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/marshall-1.jpg",
          "credit": "Donald Marshall"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## Section 35 and the Sparrow Test\nIf Leo can prove he has a 'right' to trade, the court must then apply the **Sparrow Test**. This is a four-part legal test used to decide if the government is allowed to interfere with an Indigenous right. \n\n1. **Is there an infringement?** (Clearly, the raid stopped Leo from trading).\n2. **Is there a compelling and substantial objective?** (The government must show they are protecting something very important, like the environment or public safety).\n3. **Is the 'Honour of the Crown' upheld?** (Did the government try to consult with the community first? Did they act with integrity?)\n4. **Is there as little infringement as possible?** (Could they have achieved their safety goal without raiding and arresting everyone?)\n\nLeo argues the government fails the test. They didn't consult with the Sipekne’katik Chief, and they chose the most aggressive option (a raid) instead of a conversation. The Crown, however, argues that 'public safety' is the ultimate compelling objective. They believe that because cannabis is an intoxicant, they have a right to control it to keep it out of the hands of children and to ensure no one gets sick from contaminated products. The legal battle is now over whether 'safety' is a good enough excuse to ignore a treaty.\n\n",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/treaty-document-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "Constitutional Law Archive"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## Economic Impact Data\nIntelligence reports from the Sipekne’katik First Nation indicate that 'The Trading Post' had a significant positive impact on the local economy before it was shut down. The shop employed 15 full-time staff members, all of whom were from the community. Furthermore, a percentage of the profits was donated back to the community for a lunch program at the local school and for elder care. This data is crucial because it helps define what a 'Moderate Livelihood' actually looks like in 2025. It’s not just about one person getting rich; it’s about a community sustaining itself.\n\nIntel suggests that 'Moderate Livelihood' is a term the government has deliberately left website vague to avoid giving up too much power. By keeping the definition small, the Crown can limit Indigenous competition. Strategic analysis suggests that if the Court adopts a 'broad' definition of livelihood, it will empower First Nations to move toward economic independence. However, if the Court adopts a 'narrow' definition, it will keep First Nations dependent on government funding. The outcome of this case will directly affect the 'Economic Reconciliation' scores for Canada, which are currently being monitored by international human rights organizations.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/heresleo-AI.jpg",
          "credit": "Historic Document AI"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "slide_4",
      "shortTitle": "The Crown",
      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT 4: THE SAFETY MANDATE",
      "interactionPrompt": "FIELD ANALYSIS: Evaluate the Crown's argument that public safety overrides treaty rights in the case of intoxicants.",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## The Crown’s Case\nThe Province of Nova Scotia is not arguing that the 1752 Treaty is fake or that the Mi'kmaq have no rights. Instead, they are arguing about the 'Limits' of those rights. The Crown Prosecutor argues that in a modern society, no right can be 'absolute.' For example, you have a right to move around freely, but you still have to follow the speed limit. The Crown believes that the sale of intoxicants like cannabis falls into this category. They argue that when a substance can affect people's health and brain function, the government has a responsibility to oversee it.\n\nThe Crown’s perspective is that 'The Trading Post' was essentially a 'lawless' operation because it didn't use the province's tracking system. In the 'legal' cannabis market, every plant is tracked from the moment it is a seed until it is sold at the counter. This is done to ensure no 'black market' weed gets into the system and that the product is free from pesticides. The Crown argues that by skipping these rules, Leo was creating a 'Public Health Risk.' They see themselves not as 'oppressors,' but as the protectors of the public, ensuring that every citizen—Indigenous or not—has access to a safe and regulated product. They argue that if they allow Leo to ignore the rules, it will create a 'two-tier' system where some businesses have to follow expensive safety laws while others don't.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/nslc-cannabis'-cbc.jpg",
          "credit": "CBC"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## Public Safety Justification\nUnder Canadian law, a province can justify limiting a Section 35 right if they can prove a 'compelling and substantial' public objective. Public safety is the strongest objective a government can have. In court, the Crown is focusing on the risk of 'toxic substances.' They argue that because cannabis is often grown in large greenhouses, it can develop mould or be treated with dangerous chemicals. Without a government inspector checking the facility, there is no way to know if the product is safe. They also point to the danger of 'cross-contamination' with harder drugs like fentanyl, which has become a major crisis in Nova Scotia.\n\nThe legal argument is that the Province’s **Fiduciary Duty** to protect its citizens includes a duty to ensure that all drugs sold in the province are tested in an accredited lab. They claim that the 1752 Treaty signers could never have anticipated a market for highly potent, lab-grown THC products. Therefore, the 'Truckhouse' right should not apply to something so potentially dangerous. They argue that the *Cannabis Act* is a 'valid law of general application' that was passed for the good of all Canadians, and that it should be 'paramount' (meaning it wins) over any local Band Council Resolution. They believe that 'sovereignty' does not include the right to create a public health hazard.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/leo-test-report.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## Retail Control Intelligence\nIntelligence from the Nova Scotia Liquor Corporation (NSLC) indicates that the financial pressure on the province is real. The NSLC brings in hundreds of millions of dollars in tax revenue, much of which goes to funding hospitals and schools. Intelligence reports show that in towns near First Nation dispensaries, NSLC sales have dropped by as much as 15%. This suggests that the 'Public Safety' argument may be a 'strategic narrative' designed to protect government revenue. If the province loses its monopoly on cannabis, it could lose millions in tax dollars.\n\nStrategic analysis indicates that the Crown is worried about a 'slippery slope.' If they allow Leo to sell cannabis without a license, what stops someone from opening a 'Treaty Gas Station' that doesn't pay gas taxes, or a 'Treaty Casino' that doesn't follow gambling laws? The intelligence suggests the Crown is fighting this case so hard because they want to prevent a future where the Province loses the power to tax and regulate businesses on Indigenous land. They see this as a battle for the very foundation of provincial authority. The intel warns that if the Crown loses, the Province may try to find 'other ways' to interfere with Indigenous trade, such as using environmental laws or zoning regulations.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/nslc-cannabis'-cbc.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        }
      }
