      "shortTitle": "The Future",
      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT 6: THE FINAL VERDICT",
      "interactionPrompt": "FIELD ANALYSIS: As a Clerk, will you recommend a 'Living Tree' interpretation or a 'Regulatory' one? Justify your choice.",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## Decision Day\nThe oral arguments have concluded, and the courtroom is silent. The nine Justices of the Supreme Court have retired to their private chambers to deliberate. You, as the Senior Law Clerk, have been tasked with drafting the 'Internal Memo' that will guide their final decision. You have reviewed the 1752 Treaty, the details of the raid, the *Marshall* decision, the Crown's safety concerns, and the new requirements of UNDRIP. The weight of history is on your shoulders. You must decide if 'Peace and Friendship' means that the government must respect Indigenous trade, or if 'Public Safety' means the Province always has the final word.\n\nIf you find for Leo, you are telling the country that the 'Living Tree' of the Constitution is large enough to include modern Indigenous businesses. You are saying that reconciliation requires giving up some provincial power. If you find for the Crown, you are saying that in a modern state, everyone must follow the same rules to ensure safety, even if it means limiting a treaty right. There is no easy answer. If you side with Leo, you might encourage more 'unregulated' shops. If you side with the Crown, you might spark a generation of protests and blockades. The Justices are waiting. What is your recommendation?",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/courtrroom-1.jpg",
          "credit": "Supreme Court Archive"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## The Weight of Precedent\nEvery word you write in your memo will help set 'Precedent'—a rule that every lower court in Canada must follow for decades. If you recommend that the 'Moderate Livelihood' right from the *Marshall* case should be expanded to include cannabis, you are effectively opening the door for First Nations to run their own gas stations, pharmacies, and liquor stores. This would be the largest shift in economic power in Canadian history. You must also consider the **Honour of the Crown**. This is the principle that the government must act with 'scrupulous fairness' and 'integrity' in all its dealings with Indigenous peoples.\n\nDid the Province act with integrity when they sent in the police instead of calling the Chief? Or was the 'safety risk' so urgent that they had no choice? As a clerk, you must evaluate if the 'Sparrow Test' was satisfied. If the government could have achieved safety through negotiation, but chose force instead, then the 'Honour of the Crown' might have been breached. Your legal analysis must be flawless, because if the Supreme Court gets this wrong, it could take another 20 years to fix the damage to the relationship between the Crown and the Mi'kmaq nation. The legal integrity of Canada's constitution is in your hands.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/feather.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## The Long-Term Forecast\nIntelligence forecasting predicts two very different futures for Nova Scotia. **Future A (The Partnership Path):** If the court rules for Leo, it will force the Province to sit down and sign an 'Economic Treaty' with the Mi'kmaq. This would lead to a shared safety system where both the Province and the First Nation inspect products together. Intelligence suggests this would lead to high levels of trust, lower crime, and a booming Indigenous middle class. **Future B (The Conflict Path):** If the court rules for the Crown, it will confirm that provincial laws can crush treaty rights. Intelligence predicts that this will lead to 'Deep Resentment.' Younger generations of Mi'kmaq may lose all faith in the courts and turn toward more aggressive blockades of highways and railways.\n\nStrategic analysis indicates that 'The Trading Post' is just the first of many such shops. Even if Leo loses, another shop will likely open next month. The intel suggests that 'you can't arrest your way out of a treaty dispute.' The intelligence community believes that a ruling that forces the government to *negotiate* rather than *raid* is the only path to long-term stability. As you finish your memo, you must decide: will you recommend a path that leads to the courtroom, or a path that leads to the negotiation table? Your analysis will decide if the 'Peace and Friendship' of 1752 still exists in 2025.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/judgement-1-ai.jpg",
